name: Akt
comment: Found in the C-terminal hydrophobic motif. Phosphorylation at this site by mTORC2 stimulates Akt activity (Sarbassov et al., 2005).

name: Akt
comment: Found in the activation loop of the kinase domain and is phosphorylated by PDK1 (Alessi et al., 1997; Stephens et al., 1998; Stokoe et al., 1997). This precedes phosphorylation at a second site (S474) for complete activation (e.g., Humphrey et al., 2013).

name: AS160
comment: Promotes 14-3-3 binding (although T649 is the primary binding site). Suggested to disrupt the GTPase-activating (GAP) function of AS160 and promote translocation of the GLUT4 glucose transporter to the plasma membrane, increasing glucose uptake (Sano et al., 2003; Ramm et al., 2006; Geraghty et al., 2007).

name: AS160
comment: Promotes 14-3-3 binding (although T649 is the primary binding site). Suggested to disrupt the GTPase-activating (GAP) function of AS160 and promote translocation of the GLUT4 glucose transporter to the plasma membrane, increasing glucose uptake (Sano et al., 2003; Ramm et al., 2006; Geraghty et al., 2007).

name: AS160
comment: Promotes 14-3-3 binding (although T649 is the primary binding site). Suggested to disrupt the GTPase-activating (GAP) function of AS160 and promote translocation of the GLUT4 glucose transporter to the plasma membrane, increasing glucose uptake (Sano et al., 2003; Ramm et al., 2006; Geraghty et al., 2007).

name: AS160
comment: Promotes 14-3-3 binding (although T649 is the primary binding site). Suggested to disrupt the GTPase-activating (GAP) function of AS160 and promote translocation of the GLUT4 glucose transporter to the plasma membrane, increasing glucose uptake (Sano et al., 2003; Ramm et al., 2006; Geraghty et al., 2007).

name: BAD
comment: Promotes 14-3-3 binding, preventing BAD from heterodimerising with Bcl-XL, thus promoting cell survival and inhibiting apoptosis (Zha et al., 1996; Tan et al., 1999).

name: BAD
comment: Promotes 14-3-3 binding, preventing BAD from heterodimerising with Bcl-XL, thus promoting cell survival and inhibiting apoptosis (Zha et al., 1996; Datta et al., 1997).

name: Brf1
comment: Promotes 14-3-3 binding. This impairs its role in degrading mRNA molecules that contain AU-rich elements. 14-3-3 binding also protects Brf1 from degradation, perhaps to enable rapid mRNA decay once insulin stimulus is removed (Schmidlin et al., 2004; Benjamin et al., 2006).

name: Edc3
comment: Promotes 14-3-3 binding, which impairs its role in mRNA decay and translation repression at p-bodies (Larance et al., 2010). This provides one avenue for insulin to increase protein synthesis.

name: Eif4b
comment: p70S6K phosphorylates eIF4B at this site, which promotes association with the eIF3 scaffold in the translation pre-initiation complex. This enhances the helicase activity of eIF4A, melting inhibitory secondary structures in the 5' UTR of mRNAs. This enables the 40S ribosomal subunit to bind and initiate translation (Raught et al., 2004; Holz et al., 2005).

name: Eif4ebp1
comment: mTORC1 phosphorylates EIF4EBP1 (4E-BP1) at several residues. This causes 4E-BP1 to dissociate from eIF4E, which enables eIF4E to bind the 5' cap of mRNAs, resulting in the initiation of translation (Mothe-Satney et al., 2000; Brunn et al., 1997).

name: Eif4ebp1
comment: mTORC1 phosphorylates EIF4EBP1 (4E-BP1) at several residues. This causes 4E-BP1 to dissociate from eIF4E, which enables eIF4E to bind the 5' cap of mRNAs, resulting in the initiation of translation (Mothe-Satney et al., 2000; Brunn et al., 1997).

name: Eif4ebp1
comment: mTORC1 phosphorylates EIF4EBP1 (4E-BP1) at several residues. This causes 4E-BP1 to dissociate from eIF4E, which enables eIF4E to bind the 5' cap of mRNAs, resulting in the initiation of translation (Mothe-Satney et al., 2000; Brunn et al., 1997).

name: eNOS
comment: Activates eNOS, which increases the production of nitric oxide, a signaling molecule that plays a role in numerous processes including vasodilation (Dimmeler et al., 1999).

name: Erk1
comment: MEK1/2 phosphorylates ERK1/2 within the 'activation lip' at T203/Y205 in ERK1 and T183/Y185 in ERK2 (Payne et al., 1991; Robbins et al., 1993; Butch & Guan, 1996; Her et al., 1993). Phosphorylation is favoured first at the tyrosine residue before the threonine residue (Ferrell & Bhatt, 1997; Haystead et al., 1992). This leads to activation of ERK1/2, enabling regulation of a diverse range of cellular responses to external stimuli (Roskoski, 2012). ERK1/2 also has the ability to autophosphorylate itself at these residues (Robbins et al., 1993; Her et al., 1993), but a 'gatekeeper' residue prevents this, maintaining low ERK1/2 activity in the absence of stimuli (Emrick et al., 2006).

name: Erk1
comment: MEK1/2 phosphorylates ERK1/2 within the 'activation lip' at T203/Y205 in ERK1 and T183/Y185 in ERK2 (Payne et al., 1991; Robbins et al., 1993; Butch & Guan, 1996; Her et al., 1993). name: Erk2
comment: MEK1/2 phosphorylates ERK1/2 within the 'activation lip' at T203/Y205 in ERK1 and T183/Y185 in ERK2 (Payne et al., 1991; Robbins et al., 1993; Butch & Guan, 1996; Her et al., 1993). comment: MEK1/2 phosphorylates ERK1/2 within the 'activation lip' at T203/Y205 in ERK1 and T183/Y185 in ERK2 (Payne et al., 1991; Robbins et al., 1993; Butch & Guan, 1996; Her et al., 1993). name: Foxo3a
comment: Promotes 14-3-3 binding, sequestering Foxo3a in the cytoplasm. This prevents its regulation of target genes, including those involved in apoptosis (Brunet et al., 1999; Brunet et al., 2002).

name: Grb10
comment: Enhances the stability of Grb10. Evidence suggests that this leads to feedback regulation of insulin signaling, either through the insulin receptor or by influencing mTORC1 (Hsu et al., 2011; Yu et al., 2011; Liu et al., 2014).

name: GSK3a
comment: GSK3a/b are unique kinases in that they require substrates to be phosphorylated at the residue +4 of the GSK3a/b target site. The GSK3 domain that binds this 'priming site' is occupied by the GSK3 N-terminus when S21/S9 (GSK3a/b) is phosphorylated by Akt (Frame et al., 2001). This leads to disrupted GSK3 activity (Cross et al., 1995). This not only derepresses glycogen synthesis (Eldar-Finkelman et al., 1996), for which GSK3 is named, but influences a wide range of cellular processes (reviewed in Woodgett, 2001).

name: GSK3b
comment: GSK3a/b are unique kinases in that they require substrates to be phosphorylated at the residue +4 of the GSK3a/b target site. The GSK3 domain that binds this 'priming site' is occupied by the GSK3 N-terminus when S21/S9 (GSK3a/b) is phosphorylated by Akt (Frame et al., 2001). This leads to disrupted GSK3 activity (Cross et al., 1995). This not only derepresses glycogen synthesis (Eldar-Finkelman et al., 1996), for which GSK3 is named, but influences a wide range of cellular processes (reviewed in Woodgett, 2001).

name: Gys
comment: GSK3 phosphorylates Gys at consecutive serines (S641, S645, S649, S653) in a C- to N-terminal direction - once S641 is phosphorylated, Gys activity is reduced (Embi et al., 1980; Rylatt et al., 1980; Skurat & Roach, 1995; Wang & Roach, 1993). Upon insulin stimulation, GSK3 is inhibited, derepressing Gys and thus stimulating glycogen synthesis (Schafer et al., 2004; Roach et al., 2012).

name: Gys
comment: GSK3 phosphorylates Gys at consecutive serines (S641, S645, S649, S653) in a C- to N-terminal direction - once S641 is phosphorylated, Gys activity is reduced (Embi et al., 1980; Rylatt et al., 1980; Skurat & Roach, 1995; Wang & Roach, 1993). Upon insulin stimulation, GSK3 is inhibited, derepressing Gys and thus stimulating glycogen synthesis (Schafer et al., 2004; Roach et al., 2012).

name: HSF1
comment: In response to growth factors, MAPK phosphorylates HSF1 at S307, which primes GSK3 to phosphorylate at S303 (Chu et al., 1996). This promotes 14-3-3 binding, sequestering HSF1 in the cytoplasm and thus repressing its transcriptional activity (Wang et al., 2003). This downregulates the heat shock response during processes stimulated by growth-factors, such as cellular proliferation.

name: HSF1
comment: In response to growth factors, MAPK phosphorylates HSF1 at S307, which primes GSK3 to phosphorylate at S303 (Chu et al., 1996). This promotes 14-3-3 binding, sequestering HSF1 in the cytoplasm and thus repressing its transcriptional activity (Wang et al., 2003). This downregulates the heat shock response during processes stimulated by growth-factors, such as cellular proliferation.

name: HSF1
comment: In response to stresses such as heat shock, mTORC1 phosphorylates HSF1 at S326, leading to the upregulation of heat-shock proteins such as Hsp70 (Chou et al., 2012).

name: Hsl
comment: PKA phosphorylates HSL at several residues (Anthonsen et al., 1998; Krintel et al., 2008), including S557 and S559. This results in activation of HSL, promoting lipolysis and thus mobilisation of energy stores during exercise or starvation.

name: Hsl
comment: PKA phosphorylates HSL at several residues (Anthonsen et al., 1998; Krintel et al., 2008), including S557 and S559. This results in activation of HSL, promoting lipolysis and thus mobilisation of energy stores during exercise or starvation.

name: InsR
comment: Upon binding insulin, the insulin receptor phosphorylates itself at several residues (White et al., 1988; Tavaré & Denton, 1988; Kruszynska et al., 1990), leading to its activation (Murakami & Rosen, 1991) and stimulation of insulin-responsive pathways, such as glucose uptake in fat and muscle.

name: InsR
comment: Upon binding insulin, the insulin receptor phosphorylates itself at several residues (White et al., 1988; Tavaré & Denton, 1988; Kruszynska et al., 1990), leading to its activation (Murakami & Rosen, 1991) and stimulation of insulin-responsive pathways, such as glucose uptake in fat and muscle.

name: InsR
comment: Upon binding insulin, the insulin receptor phosphorylates itself at several residues (White et al., 1988; Tavaré & Denton, 1988; Kruszynska et al., 1990), leading to its activation (Murakami & Rosen, 1991) and stimulation of insulin-responsive pathways, such as glucose uptake in fat and muscle.

name: Irs1
comment: Following insulin stimulation, S522 of IRS-1 is phosphorylated, with evidence suggesting that this is mediated by p70S6K (Shah & Hunter, 2006). Phosphorylation at this residue reduces tyrosine phosphorylation of IRS-1 (Giraud et al., 2007). This provides a feedback loop that regulates insulin signaling.

name: Irs1
comment: Upon insulin stimulation, IRS-1 is phosphorylated by the insulin receptor at numerous tyrosine residues. These serve as docking sites for SH2-binding proteins. From the phosphosites shown, Y608 (and Y460 to some extent) bind the p85 subunit of PI3K (Sun et al., 1993), mediating the PI3K/Akt pathway; Y891 binds Grb2 to activate Ras/MAPK (Sun et al., 1993; Myers et al., 1994); Y1173 binds SHPTP2 to also activate Ras/MAPK (Sun et al., 1993; Noguchi et al., 1994). Thus, IRS-1 acts as a divergence point, stimulating multiple signaling pathways in response to insulin.

name: Irs1
comment: Upon insulin stimulation, IRS-1 is phosphorylated by the insulin receptor at numerous tyrosine residues. These serve as docking sites for SH2-binding proteins. name: Mekk3
comment: SGK1 phosphorylates MEKK3 (MAP3K3) at S337 (and S166), reducing its kinase activity (Chun et al., 2003). Since MEKK3 regulates the stress-activated (SAPK) and mitogen-activated (MAPK) protein kinase pathways, this provides a way for SGK1 to turn off these pathways, enabling cross-talk between kinase signaling pathways.

name: MSK1
comment: The mitogen- and stress-activated kinase 1 (MSK1) is initially phosphorylated by p38 MAPK and ERK1 (Markou & Lazou, 2002; McCoy et al., 2005), including at residue T645. This enables MSK1 to use its C-terminal kinase domain to autophosphorylate itself at several sites, including the hydrophobic motif at S375. This activates the N-terminal kinase domain, enabling MSK1 to phosphorylate its substrates (McCoy et al., 2005). This allows the cell to respond to both growth factors and cellular stress through the same kinase (e.g., Deak et al., 1998).

name: mTOR
comment: Upon activation, mTOR autophosphorylates itself at S2481 (Peterson et al., 2000), being observed in both complexes mTORC1 and mTORC2 (Soliman et al., 2010). Although diagnostic of mTOR activity, the physiological significance of this autophosphorylation site remains elusive.

name: mTOR
comment: Upon activation, mTOR autophosphorylates itself at S2481 (Peterson et al., 2000), being observed in both complexes mTORC1 and mTORC2 (Soliman et al., 2010). Although diagnostic of mTOR activity, the physiological significance of this autophosphorylation site remains elusive.

name: mTOR
comment: Originally considered an Akt target (Sekulić et al., 2000; Navé et al., 1999), more recent evidence suggests that S2448 is actually phosphorylated by p70S6K (Chiang & Abraham, 2005; Holz & Blenis, 2005). This presents a feedback loop, although its function has not been elucidated. Since S2448 lies within the repressor domain, it has been speculated that phosphorylation at this site represses mTOR activity (Sekulić et al., 2000), but does not affect mTORC1 complex formation (Rosner et al., 2010). Please note that although this phosphosite has been placed on the mTORC2 track, it can be found in both mTORC1 and mTORC2 (Rosner et al., 2010).

name: Ndrg1
comment: SGK kinases phosphorylate T328, S330, T346, T356, and T366 of NDRG1 (the latter three found within a triple 10-residue repeat sequence) (Murray et al., 2004; Murakami et al., 2010). This primes NDRG1 for phosphorylation by GSK3 (Murray et al., 2004). Phosphorylation of NDRG1 influences its role in stress responses, such as the suppression of NF-kB signaling and CXC chemokine production (Murakami et al., 2010).

name: Ndrg1
comment: SGK kinases phosphorylate T328, S330, T346, T356, and T366 of NDRG1 (the latter three found within a triple 10-residue repeat sequence) (Murray et al., 2004; Murakami et al., 2010). This primes NDRG1 for phosphorylation by GSK3 (Murray et al., 2004). Phosphorylation of NDRG1 influences its role in stress responses, such as the suppression of NF-kB signaling and CXC chemokine production (Murakami et al., 2010).

name: Ndrg2
comment: SGK kinases phosphorylate T330, S332, and T348 of NDRG2 - there is some evidence that this primes NDRG2 for phosphorylation by GSK3 (Murray et al., 2004). The functional consequences of this have not been well-studied.

name: Ndrg2
comment: SGK kinases phosphorylate T330, S332, and T348 of NDRG2 - there is some evidence that this primes NDRG2 for phosphorylation by GSK3 (Murray et al., 2004). The functional consequences of this have not been well-studied.

name: p70S6K
comment: mTORC1 phosphorylates p70S6K at T412 (Pearson et al., 1995; Han et al., 1995), found within a hydrophobic motif downstream of the catalytic domain. This promotes p70S6K to phosphorylate numerous proteins (e.g., eIF4B) to initiate protein synthesis. As pT412 was absent in our phosphoproteomic dataset (Humphrey et al., 2013), for illustrative purposes we have used data on pT444, both of which are mTORC1-regulated sites (Hsu et al., 2011) and respond with similar kinetics to insulin in adipocytes (Humphrey et al., 2013).

name: p90RSK
comment: MAPK/ERK phosphorylates p90RSK at several residues, including S352 (human S363) (Dalby et al., 1998). This residue is found within the N-terminal kinase domain, contributing to the activation of p90RSK.

name: Pde3b
comment: Promotes 14-3-3 binding and increased Pde3b activity (Kitamura et al., 1999; Onuma et al., 2002). Pde3b catalyses hydrolysis of cAMP, influencing cAMP-dependent processes. For instance, this deactivates hormone-sensitive lipase (HSL) and lipolysis in adipocytes.

name: Pfkfb2
comment: There is strong evidence to suggest that PFKFB2 (heart PFK-2) is phosphorylated at S469 and S486 by Akt, leading to 14-3-3 binding and increased activity (Deprez et al., 1997; Pozuelo et al., 2003; Moon et al., 2011). This elevates levels of its product, fructose-2,6-bisphosphate, which stimulates glycolysis.

name: Pfkfb2
comment: There is strong evidence to suggest that PFKFB2 (heart PFK-2) is phosphorylated at S469 and S486 by Akt, leading to 14-3-3 binding and increased activity (Deprez et al., 1997; Pozuelo et al., 2003; Moon et al., 2011). This elevates levels of its product, fructose-2,6-bisphosphate, which stimulates glycolysis.

name: Plin1
comment: Promotes the access of lipases to lipid droplets in adipocytes, leading to lipid droplet breakdown and lipolysis (Marcinkiewicz et al., 2006; Miyoshi et al., 2007). This serves to mobilise energy during fasting and exercise.

name: Pras40
comment: Akt phosphorylates PRAS40 at T247 (Kovacina et al., 2003; Sancak et al., 2007; Vander et al., 2007), which promotes mTORC1 to phosphorylate PRAS40 at multiple sites, including S184 (Nascimento et al., 2010; Oshiro et al., 2007). Together, these phosphorylation events cause PRAS40 to dissociate from mTORC1 and bind 14-3-3. Combined with Akt-mediated TSC2 phosphorylation, this results in mTORC1 activation.

name: Pras40
comment: Akt phosphorylates PRAS40 at T247 (Kovacina et al., 2003; Sancak et al., 2007; Vander et al., 2007), which promotes mTORC1 to phosphorylate PRAS40 at multiple sites, including S184 (Nascimento et al., 2010; Oshiro et al., 2007). Together, these phosphorylation events cause PRAS40 to dissociate from mTORC1 and bind 14-3-3. Combined with Akt-mediated TSC2 phosphorylation, this results in mTORC1 activation.

name: Rps6
comment: p70S6K phosphorylates RPS6 (S6), a component of the 40S ribosomal subunit, at several sites, including S236 and S240 (Ferrari et al., 1991). Some studies indicate that this results in selective translation of a subset of mRNAs, 5'TOP mRNAs, (e.g., Jefferies et al., 1997), but this remains controversial (e.g., Barth-Baus et al., 2002; Ruvinsky et al., 2005). There is also evidence that phosphorylation promotes binding to the 7-methylguanosine cap-binding complex to initiate translation (Roux et al., 2007), but studies have also shown that phosphorylation reduces protein synthesis, slows cell division, and increases cell size (e.g., Ruvinsky et al., 2005). Thus, the physiological outcome of S6 phosphorylation remains unclear.

name: Rps6
comment: p70S6K phosphorylates RPS6 (S6), a component of the 40S ribosomal subunit, at several sites, including S236 and S240 (Ferrari et al., 1991). Some studies indicate that this results in selective translation of a subset of mRNAs, 5'TOP mRNAs, (e.g., Jefferies et al., 1997), but this remains controversial (e.g., Barth-Baus et al., 2002; Ruvinsky et al., 2005). There is also evidence that phosphorylation promotes binding to the 7-methylguanosine cap-binding complex to initiate translation (Roux et al., 2007), but studies have also shown that phosphorylation reduces protein synthesis, slows cell division, and increases cell size (e.g., Ruvinsky et al., 2005). Thus, the physiological outcome of S6 phosphorylation remains unclear.

name: Sin1
comment: Akt phosphorylates SIN1, a component of the mTORC2 complex. This activates mTORC2 - amongst its substrates is Akt, thus potentiating a feed-forward signaling loop (Humphrey et al., 2013).

name: SOS1
comment: MAP kinase (MAPK/ERK) phosphorylates SOS1 at several residues, including S1179 and S1183, which causes dissociation of the Sos1-Grb2 complex (Corbalan-Garcia et al., 1996). Since Sos1-Grb2 connects receptor tyrosine kinases to Ras and MAPK downstream, this serves as a feedback mechanism for Ras/MAPK signaling (e.g., Cherniack et al., 1995).

name: SOS1
comment: MAP kinase (MAPK/ERK) phosphorylates SOS1 at several residues, including S1179 and S1183, which causes dissociation of the Sos1-Grb2 complex (Corbalan-Garcia et al., 1996). Since Sos1-Grb2 connects receptor tyrosine kinases to Ras and MAPK downstream, this serves as a feedback mechanism for Ras/MAPK signaling (e.g., Cherniack et al., 1995).

name: TAK1
comment: Protein kinase A (PKA) phosphorylates TAK1 at S439. This allows cAMP/PKA-dependent signals, such as prostaglandin E2, to enhance downstream signaling pathways, including MAPK and NF-kB, subsequently promoting osteoclast differentiation (Kobayashi et al., 2005). This is in concordance with the role that TAK1 plays in directing differentiation away from adipogenesis (Suzawa et al., 2003).

name: TSC2
comment: Akt phosphorylates TSC2 at several sites, including S939, S981 and T1465 (Manning et al., 2002; Inoki et al., 2002; Cai et al., 2006). Whilst there is conflicting evidence about whether this affects its interaction with binding partner TSC1 (e.g., Cai et al., 2006) or the stability of TSC2 itself (Inoki et al., 2002; Dan et al., 2002), studies suggest TSC2 phosphorylation promotes 14-3-3 binding and its dissociation from the lysosome (Liu et al., 2002; Cai et al., 2006; Menon et al., 2014). This uncouples TSC2 from its substrate, GTP-binding protein Rheb, an mTORC1 activator (Cai et al., 2006; Menon et al., 2014). This ultimately derepresses Rheb, facilitating its GTP loading, and subsequently activates mTORC1, promoting protein and lipid synthesis in response to mitogenic and nutrient stimuli.

name: TSC2
comment: Akt phosphorylates TSC2 at several sites, including S939, S981 and T1465 (Manning et al., 2002; Inoki et al., 2002; Cai et al., 2006). name: ULK1
comment: mTORC1 phosphorylates Ulk1 at S757, which affects the interaction between Ulk1 and AMPK (Kim et al., 2011; Shang et al., 2011). Although there is conflicting evidence about the direction and effect of this interaction, there is a consensus that this prevents autophagy when nutrients are not limiting.

name: NHE1
comment: Promotes 14-3-3 binding and increased Na+/H+ exchange, which leads to cell alkalinization (Takahashi et al., 1999; Lehoux et al., 2001). Whilst this has been shown to exacerbate myocardial ischemia and reperfusion injury (Maekawa et al., 2006), it may also be necessary for cell cycle progression (Meima et al., 2009).

name: PRAS40
comment: To the best of our knowledge, this site is not well-characterized in the literature and thus the consequences of phosphorylating this site are not clear.

name: SOS1
comment: To the best of our knowledge, this site is not well-characterized in the literature and thus the consequences of phosphorylating this site are not clear.

name: SOS1
comment: To the best of our knowledge, this site is not well-characterized in the literature and thus the consequences of phosphorylating this site are not clear.
